05837nam a22006375i 9780226923314DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132002ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802269233147 a10.7208/97802269233142doi  a(DE-B1597)524544  a(OCoLC)1045074035  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aPSY0000002bisacsh04a306.70938223/swe04aThe Sleep of Reason :bErotic Experience and Sexual Ethics in Ancient Greece and Rome /ced. by Juha Sihvola, Martha C. Nussbaum. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2013] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (457 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Forgetting Foucault: Acts, Identities, and the History of Sexuality -- tChapter Two. Erōs and Ethical Norms: Philosophers Respond to a Cultural Dilemma -- tChapter Three. Erotic Experience in the Conjugal Bed: Good Wives in Greek Tragedy -- tChapter Four. Aristophanic Sex: The Erotics of Shamelessness -- tChapter Five. The Legend of the Sacred Band -- tChapter Six. Plato, Zeno, and the Object of Love -- tChapter Seven. Aristotle on Sex and Love -- tChapter Eight. Two Women of Samos -- tChapter Nine. The First Homosexuality? -- tChapter Ten. Marriage and Sexuality in Republican Rome: A Roman Conjugal Love Story -- tChapter Eleven The Incomplete Feminism of Musonius Rufus, Platonist, Stoic, and Roman -- tChapter Twelve. Eros and Aphrodisia in the Works of Dio Chrysostom -- tChapter Thirteen. Enacting Erōs -- tChapter Fourteen. The Erotic Experience of Looking: Cultural Conflict and the Gaze in Empire Culture -- tChapter Fifteen. Agents and Victims: Constructions of Gender and Desire in Ancient Greek Love Magic -- tAppendix. Major Historical Figures Discussed -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSex is beyond reason, and yet we constantly reason about it. So, too, did the peoples of ancient Greece and Rome. But until recently there has been little discussion of their views on erotic experience and sexual ethics. The Sleep of Reason brings together an international group of philosophers, philologists, literary critics, and historians to consider two questions normally kept separate: how is erotic experience understood in classical texts of various kinds, and what ethical judgments and philosophical arguments are made about sex? From same-sex desire to conjugal love, and from Plato and Aristotle to the Roman Stoic Musonius Rufus, the contributors demonstrate the complexity and diversity of classical sexuality. They also show that the ethics of eros, in both Greece and Rome, shared a number of commonalities: a focus not only on self-mastery, but also on reciprocity; a concern among men not just for penetration and display of their power, but also for being gentle and kind, and for being loved for themselves; and that women and even younger men felt not only gratitude and acceptance, but also joy and sexual desire. Contributors: * Eva Cantarella * Kenneth Dover * Chris Faraone * Simon Goldhill * Stephen Halliwell * David M. Halperin * J. Samuel Houser * Maarit Kaimio * David Konstan * David Leitao * Martha C. Nussbaum * A. W. Price * Juha Sihvola  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh1 aCantarella, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDover, Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaraone, Christopher A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldhill, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalliwell, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c